#!/bin/sh
# runit service manager: lists every service with live status, fzf to pick,
# act, and the list re-renders so you can toggle several in a row.
# Bound to a floating kitty in dwl (like killfzf/clipfzf).
#
# Two scopes are merged into one list:
#   [sys]  system services in /etc/sv, supervised via /var/service symlinks
#          (root-owned; managed with sudo). Enable/disable = add/remove the
#          /var/service symlink.
#   [usr]  user services in ~/.local/sv, supervised directly by the per-user
#          `runsvdir ~/.local/sv` from dwl's autostart (no sudo, no symlinks —
#          the dir *is* the supervised set). Enable/disable = remove/create a
#          `down` file inside the service dir, since there's no link to drop.
#
# Glyphs:  ● running   ○ enabled but stopped   · disabled
# Keys:
#   enter   toggle running (sv up / sv down)
#   ctrl-e  enable  (sys: symlink into /var/service; usr: rm down file) + start
#   ctrl-d  disable (sys: rm /var/service symlink; usr: touch down file) + stop
#   ctrl-r  restart (sv restart)
#   tab     multi-select (action applies to every selection)
#   esc     quit
#
# Reading/managing system services touches root-owned /var/service and the
# supervisor (supervise/ dirs are 0700), so the script grabs a sudo timestamp
# up front and reuses it for the session. User services need no privileges.

AVAIL=/etc/sv               # all installed system services
RUN=/var/service            # symlinks here = enabled (supervised by runit)
USERSV="$HOME/.local/sv"    # per-user services (supervised by user runsvdir)
# NB: deliberately NOT exporting these as SVDIR globally — runit's `sv` honors
# $SVDIR, so we set it per-command for user services and let sudo drop it
# (defaulting to /var/service) for system ones.

# Cache sudo credentials once so the rest of the loop runs without re-prompting.
if ! sudo -v; then
    printf 'sudo required to manage system services.\n' >&2
    exit 1
fi

# Build the fzf input: one "glyph<TAB>scope<TAB>name" line per service.
build_list() {
    # --- system services ---------------------------------------------------
    # Basenames of currently enabled (supervised) services, space-separated
    # (so the " $x " membership tests below match on word boundaries).
    enabled=$(ls "$RUN" 2>/dev/null | tr '\n' ' ')

    # Names runit reports as running, from one batched status call.
    running=$(
        [ -n "$enabled" ] && (cd "$RUN" && sudo sv status $enabled 2>/dev/null) \
            | awk '/^run:/ { sub(/:$/, "", $2); print $2 }' | tr '\n' ' '
    )

    for path in "$AVAIL"/*; do
        [ -d "$path" ] || continue
        name=${path##*/}
        case " $running " in
            *" $name "*)
                glyph='\033[32m●\033[0m' ;;                 # green: running
            *)
                case " $enabled " in
                    *" $name "*) glyph='\033[33m○\033[0m' ;; # peach: enabled, stopped
                    *)           glyph='\033[90m·\033[0m' ;; # gray: disabled
                esac ;;
        esac
        printf "$glyph\t%s\t%s\n" 'sys' "$name"
    done

    # --- user services -----------------------------------------------------
    # runsvdir supervises every dir in ~/.local/sv directly, so there's no
    # "available but not enabled" pool: a service is disabled only when it
    # carries a `down` file (runsv reads it and won't auto-start).
    [ -d "$USERSV" ] || return

    unames=$(
        for path in "$USERSV"/*; do
            [ -f "$path/run" ] || continue
            printf '%s ' "${path##*/}"
        done
    )
    [ -n "$unames" ] || return

    urunning=$(
        SVDIR="$USERSV" sv status $unames 2>/dev/null \
            | awk '/^run:/ { sub(/:$/, "", $2); print $2 }' | tr '\n' ' '
    )

    for path in "$USERSV"/*; do
        [ -f "$path/run" ] || continue
        name=${path##*/}
        if [ -f "$path/down" ]; then
            glyph='\033[90m·\033[0m'                         # gray: disabled
        else
            case " $urunning " in
                *" $name "*) glyph='\033[32m●\033[0m' ;;     # green: running
                *)           glyph='\033[33m○\033[0m' ;;     # peach: enabled, stopped
            esac
        fi
        printf "$glyph\t%s\t%s\n" 'usr' "$name"
    done
}

while true; do
    sel=$(build_list \
            | sort -k2 \
            | fzf --ansi --no-sort --reverse --multi \
                  --delimiter='\t' --with-nth=1,2,3 \
                  --prompt 'service> ' \
                  --header $'enter: start/stop   ctrl-e: enable   ctrl-d: disable   ctrl-r: restart   tab: multi' \
                  --expect=ctrl-e,ctrl-d,ctrl-r) || exit 0

    key=$(printf '%s\n' "$sel" | head -n1)
    # Carry "scope<TAB>name" for each picked line.
    picks=$(printf '%s\n' "$sel" | tail -n +2 | awk -F'\t' 'NF>2 {print $2"\t"$3}')
    [ -n "$picks" ] || exit 0

    printf '%s\n' "$picks" | while IFS="$(printf '\t')" read -r scope name; do
        [ -n "$name" ] || continue
        if [ "$scope" = usr ]; then
            dir="$USERSV/$name"
            case "$key" in
                ctrl-e)
                    # Enable: drop the down flag, then start.
                    rm -f "$dir/down"
                    SVDIR="$USERSV" sv up "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    ;;
                ctrl-d)
                    # Disable: stop, then flag down so it won't auto-start.
                    SVDIR="$USERSV" sv down "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    touch "$dir/down"
                    ;;
                ctrl-r)
                    SVDIR="$USERSV" sv restart "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    ;;
                *)  # plain enter: toggle running state
                    if SVDIR="$USERSV" sv status "$name" 2>/dev/null | grep -q '^run:'; then
                        SVDIR="$USERSV" sv down "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    else
                        # Not running. If disabled, starting it also clears down.
                        rm -f "$dir/down"
                        SVDIR="$USERSV" sv up "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    fi
                    ;;
            esac
        else
            case "$key" in
                ctrl-e)
                    # Enable: symlink into /var/service; runit auto-starts it.
                    [ -e "$RUN/$name" ] || sudo ln -s "$AVAIL/$name" "$RUN/$name"
                    sudo sv up "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    ;;
                ctrl-d)
                    # Disable: stop, then remove the supervised symlink.
                    sudo sv down "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    [ -L "$RUN/$name" ] && sudo rm "$RUN/$name"
                    ;;
                ctrl-r)
                    sudo sv restart "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    ;;
                *)  # plain enter: toggle running state
                    if sudo sv status "$name" 2>/dev/null | grep -q '^run:'; then
                        sudo sv down "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    else
                        # Not running. If disabled, enabling is what "start" means.
                        [ -e "$RUN/$name" ] || sudo ln -s "$AVAIL/$name" "$RUN/$name"
                        sudo sv up "$name" 2>/dev/null
                    fi
                    ;;
            esac
        fi
    done
done
